Rafael Correa à Quito, let's go.
Founding the republic on socialism in the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
On Sunday, following the example of colleagues and friends, it was the latter who gave voice to the draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since, according to official results, 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, on an 80% basis of votes.
According to these results, "no" was 28%, while 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% blank cards.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it should obtain half of the votes, plus one.
On Sunday, two polls carried out at the exit of the polling stations and an estimate of a non-governmental organization had announced an overwhelming victory of the "yes", placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed in the night between Sunday and Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The "Constitution triumphed gloriously", had assured, congratulating Ecuadorians in the guayaquil governorate, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As always, Chávez and Morales congratulated Rafael Correa, as did his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The ballot, which took place calmly according to the election observation mission of the Organization of American States (OEA), was based on a text of 444 points to consolidate the "new socialism" defended by the president.
This draft Constitution devotes the state's power over the economy, reserving it the "planning of development" of a country that lives essentially from the oil extraction carried out by large foreign companies and consequently of their currency.
Conceived by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants more power to the head of state, who can be elected for two consecutive four-year terms, to have the opportunity to dissolve the assembly.
Correa has already announced its intention to exploit this amendment and re-apply its candidacy for a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also affirms the gratuitousness of health and education services, which the president began to promote in this country of 13,9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also prohibits the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched an assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts seized ten days ago.
I'm in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions held captive in the desert for ten days were reported Monday afternoon, safe and sound, in the Egyptian capital.
In the morning, they had been freed in Chad by an Egyptian commando.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived at Almaza military base, near Cairo International Airport, around 3:30 p.m., aboard a special plane.
On board a helicopter, they were transferred immediately, without being able to release any interviews to the press, to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, to be subjected to analysis.
They enjoy "good health" and no ransom was paid "to the kidnappers," said Egypt's Minister of Tourism, Zoheir Garanna, on the airstrip.
Kidnapped on September 19 during a safari in 4x4 at the foot of Mount Ouanat, bordering Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been tossed from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group consisted of 11 tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – and 8 Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of Aegyptous, the safari organiser agency.
An Egyptian security officer said that 30 members of the special forces, aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night, just before dawn.
"There were gunshots, half of the kidnappers were killed, while the others escaped," said the manager who requested to maintain anonymity.
He explained that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "flash" unit were sent to Sudan, where they would support German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini stressed, from Belgrade, the importance of the role of Italian secret agents and special forces.
We must admit that if we achieved this result, it was thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the men of our secret services, special forces," he said, without adding any further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese patrol army had claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on board which the kidnappers were found and to have killed six, including the Chadian leader of the kidnappers, and to have captured two.
According to the army the kidnappers would be linked to a Darfur rebel organization, the Sudan Liberation Movement, (SLA_U), immediately denied by the latter.
Letters - The silent majority of culture
On the front page there is a debate on the financing of culture, on which the current election campaign is focused.
All the better.
But part of our cultural life always remains in the shadows.
Who will rule to denounce the miserable sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical places that are starving?
What politician would dare remind the federal government that he is neglecting monuments and property buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we do not have any real laws that actually preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government is paying three and a half million euros for the only restoration of Chinon Castle in the Loire Valley?
With our American neighbours, it is the Constitution that affirms that heritage protection is part of national culture and that the same heritage must be protected by every citizen, every political authority and every government department, and all this by mutual agreement.
In Quebec, at the Federation of Historical Societies of Quebec, there are at least 40,000 volunteers who, grouped into 211 societies for the preservation of historical, genealogical, archives and property preserve, with little money, private archives and archaeological sites.
It is they who, often, defend our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when real estate entrepreneurs and decision-making bodies attack our forgotten remains and cemeteries with their bulldozers.
When will the right space be reserved for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalise part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states help the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was first in difficulty in Europe for the crisis in the US credit market, by partial nationalisation: the three nations will provide EUR 11.2 billion to the financial institution - insurance with interest also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands agreed at the highest level on the weekend, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Competition Commissioner.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the face of the difficulties facing the international financial market for more than a year is that of the bank Fortis, and from a certain point of view the decisions taken in this regard can be a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night all three states will hold almost half (49%) of the bank's share in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell part of its interests, including first of all the assets, especially insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week Fortis' actions began with a vertical collapse, serious signs of the institute's crisis then appeared in the second half of the week.
Analysts however agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too large to allow it to go bankrupt.
The bank's shares fell almost 12% on Friday, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January the value of the shares has decreased by more than two thirds.
Considering the current stock prices the entire capital value of the group is around 14 billion euros, but according to the bank's executives this value is not real.
The company summit imputes the collapse of Fortis shares to the uncertainties of the non-European market due to the acceptance of the US $700 billion plan.
On Monday the title slowly resumed to rise.
Friday Filip Dierckx was appointed new CEO of the bank.
The financial institution has also sought private buyers but so far no one has come forward with a worthy offer.
The Belgian Government had previously ensured that investors should not fear losing money.
There was no panic among the bank's customers, the branches were not attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis owns autonomous subsidiaries and has also acquired leasing firms.
The fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurers, based on people's medical purchase data, often refuse to enter into an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription drug data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting the henhouse to the fox" — writes the Washington Post citing Richard Dick author of the program to follow prescriptions of medicines.
Insurance companies shall make the insurance fee and the amount due in the event of claims subject to the health status of the customer and if they consider the risk too high they shall not take out the insurance.
A while ago, the client had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was not concluded until after the test was completed.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: according to the client's identification code you can easily get information from pharmacies about what medicines you have purchased in the last year and a half and from this the program shows what diseases you suffer from and what health conditions you find yourself in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers, this means that the level of fat in your blood is basically incurably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
On the market there are several versions of the program, some also determine the risk multiplier, so the insurer in addition to paper work does not remain much, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the cons, some medicines are usable for several purposes, e.g. some compounds can be used against headaches or hot flushes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from an insurance-commercial point of view, is worth as a risk increase factor, the first two are not.
For the request and processing of data, separate companies were formed and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, request the approval of the patient.
The authorities are now forcing them to do so even though they have not yet imposed negligence fines.
Some firms have recently also developed the results of laboratory tests and link them to the drug consumption data in order to provide a more precise picture of the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to data and, in parallel, the control of the use will be more and more difficult.
There is a separate law on privacy but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of the Congress there is a bill that gives the supervisory authorities control powers to specialized companies in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that connects data forwarding with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another question is that the person concerned cannot deny approval because otherwise insurers do not enter into the contract.
So then in the end hens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
