European Union and India double trade
Since the European Union and India are partners that trade in particular with each other, the agenda of the ninth summit meeting has also been dominated by this issue, as well as all other global problems.
Today there will be a Franco-Indian summit which will deal primarily with cooperation on atomic energy.
The European Union recognises the fact that India is becoming a great democratic power which should be given more voice in international affairs, but the member countries have not yet been able to decide whether to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
So there was no insistence on this issue in the ninth summit held yesterday in Marseilles.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as President-in-Office of the Union, José Manuel Barroso, Chairman of the Commission and Javier Solana, High Representative for Foreign Affairs, received the Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double in five years, i.e. increase up to EUR 100 billion, trade.
Given that trade in goods rose from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this is not too ambitious.
As a result, they have legally unified the 26 bilateral civil flight agreements, so air traffic can also start in the future.
India would like to sign the free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the deal.
The objective is to balance because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi is only ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit paid attention to global matters.
To the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and terrorism, the latter condemned in all its forms by both sides, and called for the convening of a UN conference.
They urged the conclusion of the Doha Trade Round, although both sides played a role in the failure of this.
The EU has confirmed its continued energy and climate programme, i.e. it would like to reduce emissions of harmful substances by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agrees on this, as well as on the need for a global pact at next year's climate conference and a 50% reduction in greenhouse gas production by 2050.
They also want to curb the rise in food prices and supported the call for an international meeting to examine the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister will today go to the French capital where at a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign a treaty on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive a contract worth EUR 20 billion to build Indian nuclear reactors.
According to information from our news agency, the deal would last 15 years.
