Found Steve Fossett's plane the billionaire who disappeared a year ago
The wreck of Steve Fossett's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, was found.
The wreckage was found on a plateau at 3000 meters of altitude, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammoth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the aircraft, however, there were no human remains.
The sheriff of Madeira County, John Anderson, has dispelled the remaining doubts: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is exactly what Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff then specified that no human remains were found either in the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was given for dead in February.
The U.S. Office for Transport Safety (Ntsb) indicated that a few hours after the wreck was seen, a team of investigators was sent, who then identified the device: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, missing from September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, again in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal effects had been found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
It is two documents under Fossett's name, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweatshirt.
Fossett's research had been interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of primates.
By 2002, on the sixth attempt, he had become the first man to complete the world tour on an aerodynamic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later he had traveled the world by plane and without a stop.
Among his many records, also that of having flown at 15,445 meters in height, above the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
